	Unless otherwise indicated or the context otherwise requires, references to &#8220;we,&#8221; &#8220;us,&#8221; &#8220;our,&#8221; &#8220;Nexvet,&#8221; &#8220;Nexvet Biopharma plc&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221; refer to Nexvet Biopharma public limited company and its consolidated subsidiaries.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Unless otherwise indicated or the context otherwise requires, all dollar amounts presented in this annual report on Form 10-K, or this report, are in U.S. dollars ($).&nbsp;&nbsp;This report translates certain Australian dollar amounts to U.S. dollars at the exchange rates for A$ into US$.&nbsp;&nbsp;For assets and liabilities, the exchange rate at the balance sheet date is used.&nbsp;&nbsp;For revenue and expenses and gains and losses, a weighted-average exchange rate for the period is used to translate those elements.&nbsp;&nbsp;For transactions effected in Australian dollars, the exchange rate on the date of the transaction is used.&nbsp;&nbsp;Information not in U.S. dollars is identified by &#8220;&#8364;&#8221; for Euro-denominated amounts and &#8220;A$&#8221; for Australian dollar-denominated amounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:6.67%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

</P>

&#8220;assume,&#8221; &#8220;believe,&#8221; &#8220;continue,&#8221; &#8220;could,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;intend,&#8221; &#8220;may,&#8221; &#8220;might,&#8221; &#8220;objective,&#8221; or the negative of these terms or other similar expressions are intended to identify forward-looking statements, although not all forward looking statements contain these identifying words.&nbsp;&nbsp;These forward looking statements are based on current expectations, estimates, forecasts and projections about our business and the industry in which we operate, and management&#8217;s beliefs and assumptions are not guarantees of future performance or development and involve known and unknown risks, uncertainties and other factors.

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2

<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage4"></A>
<EFX_PART_I>
<A NAME="FIS_PART_I"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU4">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	PART I
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_BUSINESS>
<A NAME="FIS_BUSINESS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM_ITEM_1_BUSINESS">
</A>
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM_ITEM_1_BUSINESS">
</A>
	Item 1. Business&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are a clinical-stage biopharmaceutical company focused on transforming the field of companion animal therapeutics by developing and commercializing novel, species-specific biologics. Biologics are therapeutic proteins derived from biological sources. As a class, biologics have transformed human medicine in recent decades and represent many of the top-selling therapies on the market today, due to advantages including a long duration of action, attractive side effect profiles and injectability.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe these advantages will translate into significant advantages for companion animal therapeutics. Our platform technology, which we refer to as &#8220;PETization,&#8221; is an algorithmic approach that enables us to rapidly create monoclonal antibodies (&#8220;mAbs&#8221;), a type of biologic, that are designed to be recognized as &#8220;self&#8221; or &#8220;native&#8221; by an animal&#8217;s immune system, a property we refer to as &#8220;100% species-specificity.&#8221; PETization is designed to build upon the safety and efficacy data from clinically tested human therapies to create new therapies for companion animals, thereby reducing clinical risk and development cost.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	mAbs are targeted antibodies produced by identical or clonal cells that are engineered to produce a specific mAb, and they are a prominent class of therapeutic biologics in humans. Our most advanced product candidates are mAbs that target and inhibit the function of nerve growth factor (&#8220;NGF&#8221;) for the control of pain associated with osteoarthritis in dogs and cats.&nbsp;&nbsp;NGF is a protein that directs nerve growth and is also involved in nerve signaling, including pain signals, and NGF inhibitors (&#8220;anti-NGFs&#8221;) seek to interrupt those signals to reduce pain.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our anti-NGF portfolio consists of ranevetmab (formerly &#8220;NV-01&#8221;) for dogs, frunevetmab (formerly &#8220;NV-02&#8221;) for cats, both in late-stage clinical development as monthly subcutaneous injectables, as well as NV-03 for horses which has completed initial proof-of-concept studies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our most clinically advanced product candidate is ranevetmab.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our pivotal efficacy and field safety study of ranevetmab met its primary efficacy endpoint demonstrating a statistically significant improvement over placebo in the assessed level of pain (p=0.041) as measured using change in Client-Specific Outcome Measures (&#8220;CSOM&#8221;) score between enrollment and day 28.&nbsp;&nbsp;This study&#8217;s design was agreed under protocol concurrence with the Center for Veterinary Medicine (&#8220;CVM&#8221;) at the United States Food and Drug Administration (&#8220;FDA&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Ranevetmab was seen to be safe and well tolerated with no significant adverse safety signals observed in the study.&nbsp;&nbsp;Clinically meaningful magnitudes of benefit and statistically significant differences over placebo were also achieved for the majority of the secondary endpoints measured in the study, which used a monthly subcutaneous injection for three months.&nbsp;&nbsp;Collectively, the results of this study constitute a substantial body of efficacy data that we have filed with the CVM and intend to use as the basis of our planned submissions for marketing authorizations in both the United States (&#8220;U.S.&#8221;) and Europe.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have a master collaboration, supply and distribution agreement, and a specific distribution agreement for ranevetmab, with Virbac S.A. (&#8220;Virbac&#8221;), one of the larger animal health companies in the world.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our next most advanced product candidate, frunevetmab, is an anti-NGF mAb for the control of pain associated with osteoarthritis in cats.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have obtained positive and statistically significant results from a proof-of-concept efficacy study and a separate pilot safety study of frunevetmab.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have also obtained positive results from a placebo-controlled, double-blinded, multi-site pilot field safety and efficacy study, which enrolled 126 cats with naturally occurring osteoarthritis. In terms of efficacy, a wide range of statistically significant improvements over placebo at multiple time points, using multiple assessment methods, were seen in this study, which used a monthly dose for two months. Frunevetmab was also seen to be safe and well-tolerated, with no significant adverse safety signals observed. Results from this study have informed preparations for a pivotal efficacy and field safety study for frunevetmab, anticipated to commence in the fourth quarter of 2016. We are seeking protocol concurrence for this study with the CVM.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We also conduct drug discovery in the areas of immuno-oncology, inflammation and allergy. In July 2015, we entered a research and development collaboration with Zenoaq, a leading animal health company based in Japan, which involves applying PETization to convert mAb candidates identified by Zenoaq into 100%&#160;species-specific candidates in the areas of immuno-oncology (cancer), inflammation and allergy.&nbsp;&nbsp;This collaboration has yielded fully caninized mAbs that bind to the immuno-oncology target known as programmed cell death protein 1 (&#8220;PD-1&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;PD-1 is the target of approved human therapies, including pembrolizumab (Keytruda) and nivolumab (Opdivo) which have demonstrated efficacy against multiple tumor types.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the U.S., the CVM and the Center for Veterinary Biologics (&#8220;CVB&#8221;) at the United States Department of Agriculture (&#8220;USDA&#8221;) and the Environmental Protection Agency (&#8220;EPA&#8221;) regulate new animal drug candidates. The USDA has confirmed its regulatory jurisdiction over anti-PD-1 mAbs, providing the opportunity for a conditional license.&nbsp;&nbsp;Conditional licensure allows a company to start selling a product on a comparatively rapid basis, under certain conditions, after a demonstration of purity and safety and if there is a reasonable expectation of efficacy for the product. While a conditional licensure is in place, the license holder must continue to develop efficacy data in order to apply for a full approval.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	We have commenced a pharmacokinetic, immunogenicity and preliminary safety proof&#8209;of&#8209;concept study for our anti-PD-1 program.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	3
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage5"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU5">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	O
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ur
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	most advanced
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	anti-inflammatory programs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	consist of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	mAb
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	candidates
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	targeting tumor necrosis factor (&#8220;anti-TNFs&#8221;)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="BACKGROUND-COLOR:#FFFFFF;">
	TNF is a protein that causes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	inflammation and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	anti-TNFs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	suppress this inflammation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	&#160;In humans, anti-TNFs include several marketed therapies
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	such as infliximab (Remicade) and adalimumab (Humira) that have been among the top-selling drugs in the world, due to their therapeutic action in a variety of inflammatory conditions. Our drug discovery team has
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	used PETization to create fully canine and f
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	ully feline anti-TNF mAbs that demonstrate high potency in neut
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	ralizing canine and feline TNF
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	Our anti-TNF mAb candidates will enter pharmacokinetic, preliminary safety and immunogenicity proof-of-concept studies in the second half of 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September 2015, we secured a biopharmaceutical manufacturing facility in Tullamore, Ireland.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have reconfigured it to be a dedicated veterinary biopharmaceutical facility with the capability to meet our anticipated future clinical and commercial production needs for drug substance.&nbsp;&nbsp;The facility is operated by our wholly-owned subsidiary BioNua Limited (&#8220;BioNua&#8221;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Since our initial public offering, we have focused on clinical development of our most advanced candidates and securing infrastructure to become a vertically integrated veterinary biopharmaceutical company.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are building a pipeline of development candidates derived from PETization in therapeutic areas where human mAbs have had significant impact.
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Product Pipeline
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are developing 100% species-specific therapeutic biologics in four key areas, all involving chronic conditions where there is significant unmet medical need in veterinary medicine: pain, immuno-oncology (cancer), inflammation, and allergy. Our most advanced product candidates are in the area of chronic pain: ranevetmab (dogs) and frunevetmab (cats). Our programs in the other three key areas vary in stage of development.&nbsp;&nbsp;The status of our programs in each of these areas is summarized below:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 1: Nexvet pipeline
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000001.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:601PX;HEIGHT:266PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 1PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:1PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-RIGHT:83.33%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:6PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:4.54%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	(1)
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	The research stage involves the selection of a biological target, selection and PETization of starting mAbs, and validation and characterization work. Our proof-of-concept, or POC, studies include four stages: pharmacokinetics, preliminary safety, immunogenicity and safety and efficacy, which are not necessarily sequential.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Development of companion animal therapeutics is typically faster and less expensive than human drug development. It requires fewer clinical trials, fewer subjects and less pre-clinical work and can be conducted directly in the target species. According to Pharmaceutical Commerce, companion animal therapeutics can obtain U.S. regulatory approval in under six&#160;years. We expect the third party costs to complete the development and manufacturing scale-up of a typical therapeutic biologic program to be approximately $10.0 to $12.0&#160;million per candidate, a reduction on our previous estimates now that we are factoring estimated cost savings generated by manufacturing activity at BioNua. By contrast, development and receipt of regulatory approval for human therapeutics may take up to 13&#160;years and development can cost hundreds of&#160;millions of dollars per drug.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The FDA requires the completion and acceptance of several key regulatory submissions before it can grant marketing approval for a new animal drug. We opened an investigational new animal drug file (&#8220;INAD&#8221;) with the FDA for ranevetmab in 2012 and for frunevetmab in 2013. After an INAD file has been opened, a series of technical sections must be filed with the CVM before an Administrative New Animal Drug Application (&#8220;NADA&#8221;) can be filed as the final major step in seeking marketing approval. For companion animals, the major technical sections include: effectiveness; target animal safety; and chemistry, manufacturing and controls (&#8220;CMC&#8221;).
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	4
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage6"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU6">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	hronic
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	P
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ain
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	in D
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ogs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ranevetmab (formerly &#8220;NV-01&#8221;) is a &#8220;100% dog&#8221; mAb targeting NGF, designed by PETization and being developed as a monthly subcutaneous injectable for chronic pain, specifically the pain associated with osteoarthritis in dogs. &#160;To date, all our clinical studies of ranevetmab assessing its potential as a therapeutic for chronic pain in dogs have supported its safety and efficacy. Ranevetmab&#8217;s injectable nature and long half-life have a number of advantages over the current standards of care for chronic canine pain, which are commonly orally administered drugs, often with daily dosing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have a master collaboration, supply and distribution agreement, and a specific distribution agreement for ranevetmab, with Virbac.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under these agreements, we appointed Virbac as our sole and exclusive distributor of ranevetmab (and any other products for which we enter into a specific distribution agreement with Virbac) in the veterinary field worldwide, except for the U.S. and Canada.&nbsp;&nbsp;For ranevetmab, Virbac must provide clinical, regulatory, marketing and sales advice, sell it, meet or exceed minimum annual net sales obligations and provide other services specified in the agreements.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will receive an agreed percentage of the commercial margin from Virbac&#8217;s sales of ranevetmab, which percentage is a fixed number between 45-55%.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have retained the rights to distribute ranevetmab in the U.S. and Canada, where we intend to market and distribute ranevetmab through a dedicated sales team and distributors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have successfully completed a pivotal efficacy and field safety study for&#160;ranevetmab, for which we obtained protocol concurrence from the FDA. This is a key clinical demonstration of efficacy, which has formed the basis of an effectiveness technical section we have filed with the FDA and will form an integral part of planned submissions we intend to file with the European Medicines Agency (EMA). We expect to initiate a pivotal safety study (also called a Target Animal Safety (&#8220;TAS&#8221;) study) in the first half of calendar 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have received protocol concurrence from the FDA CVM for this pivotal safety study.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Market Opportunity and Current Treatment Limitations
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	According to the 2015-2016 American Pet Products Association National Pet Owners Survey and the European Pet Food Industry Federation&#8217;s Facts and Figures 2014, there are approximately 78&#160;million pet dogs in the U.S. and approximately 63&#160;million pet dogs in the European Union (&#8220;EU&#8221;) and approximately 81 million pet dogs in the wider European region. Pain in dogs can be a result of chronic diseases, such as osteoarthritis, or can be produced via trauma, surgery, cancer or infection. Osteoarthritis is an age-associated degenerative condition affecting the joint tissues and, with the exception of joint replacement surgery, there are no curative treatments. The prevalence of osteoarthritis is approximately 20% in adult dogs, rising to approximately 80% of geriatric dogs (those older than eight years).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The market for canine pain management products has been growing over the last 15&#160;years. In the U.S. alone, sales of small animal pain management drugs increased from less than $10&#160;million in 1995 to nearly $284&#160;million in 2015, following the introduction in 1996 of Rimadyl, a
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (&#8220;NSAID&#8221;)
</FONT>
	. In 2015, Rimadyl sales accounted for approximately $90&#160;million of this market. The U.S. canine pain market is currently dominated by several NSAIDs, commonly orally administered drugs, often with daily dosing, which together accounted for over 83% of canine pain medication sales in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	NSAIDs account for the largest number of adverse drug events reported to the FDA, including vomiting, gastrointestinal bleeding, diarrhea, and liver and kidney toxicities. This can encourage veterinarians to adopt a &#8220;multi-modal&#8221; approach to managing chronic canine pain, which can include a variety of interventions, including drugs not approved for this indication, in order to accommodate the variable response of individual patients to NSAIDs and other therapeutic interventions. We believe that the limitations of NSAIDs create a significant commercial opportunity for the development of a novel, long-acting treatment for chronic pain that has comparable efficacy to NSAIDs without their adverse events. This view is supported by a proprietary report we commissioned from market intelligence company GfK in December 2013, which revealed that of 390 veterinarians surveyed in the U.S., United Kingdom, France and Germany, between 93% and 97% reported they would use a product such as&#160;ranevetmab for the treatment of chronic pain in dogs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Solution
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ranevetmab is a PETized mAb that inhibits the activity of NGF in dogs. NGF is elevated in the joints of dogs with osteoarthritis. NGF is produced by a variety of inflammatory and immune cells and chondrocytes, which are cells that produce and maintain cartilage. NGF acts on pain-sensing nerve fibers to increase their excitability and increase the sprouting of new nerve fibers into inflamed tissues. mAbs targeting NGF have been extensively studied in humans up to and including Phase III clinical studies and have been shown to be effective in managing osteoarthritic pain in patients.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have published a number of peer-reviewed scientific papers regarding ranevetmab.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	5
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage7"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU7">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In proof-of-concept studies, ranevetmab
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#160;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	found to be safe and well tolerated following intravenous
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	and subcutaneous
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	administration
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	in dogs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	, and to have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	pharmacokinetic
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	profile indicating
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	a prolonged circulation time
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	after a single injec
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	tion.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#160;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	These studies also provided early evidence of efficacy,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	lack of overt
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	immunogenicity, and a lack of any significant neutralizing antibody response.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The key clinical study of ranevetmab to date is the successfully completed pivotal efficacy and field safety study. This study enrolled 262 dogs with naturally occurring osteoarthritis at 12 clinical sites: six in the U.S., three in Germany and three in France. This placebo-controlled, randomized, double-blind study was conducted to Good Clinical Practice and used three doses, each 28 days apart. Dogs were randomly assigned to ranevetmab or placebo on a 2:1 ratio. The key efficacy assessments were conducted using recognized owner assessment metrology instruments, namely the Client-Specific Outcome Measures (&#8220;CSOM&#8221;) and the Canine Brief Pain Inventory (&#8220;CBPI&#8221;). CSOM, CBPI and veterinarian assessments were measured at enrollment and on days 14, 28, 56 and 84. The study&#8217;s design was agreed under protocol concurrence with the FDA CVM.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 2: Summary CSOM data from the pivotal efficacy and field safety study of ranevetmab
<FONT STYLE="BACKGROUND-COLOR:#FFFFFF;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000002.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:341PX;HEIGHT:282PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	CSOM assesses change over time in three activities of the pet, selected by the owner, to evaluate the pet&#8217;s pain and disability. In this study, each CSOM activity received a score between 0 and 4, for a total maximum score of 12. CSOM &#8220;success&#8221; in a dog was pre-defined as an overall improvement of at least 2 in the total CSOM score with no worsening of any individual activity&#8217;s score. On the rate of CSOM success, expressed as a percentage, a statistically significant improvement over placebo was achieved in ranevetmab treated dogs at days 28 (p=0.0414), 56 (p=0.0268) and 84 (p=0.0448). The day 28 endpoint was prescribed as the primary endpoint, as concurred with the CVM, and this was successfully met.&nbsp;&nbsp;The CSOM Global Assessment is an evaluation designed to assess overall owner experience with the treatment.&nbsp;&nbsp;It was performed once in this study, at day 28.&nbsp;&nbsp;Treated dogs achieved a statistically significant improvement over placebo on this endpoint (p=0.0291).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	6
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage8"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU8">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 3: Summary CBPI data from the pivotal efficacy and field safety study of ranevetmab
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000003.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:318PX;HEIGHT:267PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Like CSOM, CBPI is an owner assessment tool used to evaluate a pet&#8217;s pain and disability. Unlike CSOM, which is tailored to individual animals, CBPI has fixed evaluation criteria. On the rate of CBPI success, expressed as a percentage, a statistically significant improvement over placebo was achieved in treated dogs at days 14 (p=0.0237), 28 (p=0.0227) and 56 (p=0.0046). The day 14, 28 and 56 time points also achieved statistical significance in median change from enrollment in both components of the CBPI: a Pain Severity Score (&#8220;PSS&#8221;) and a Pain Interference Score (&#8220;PIS&#8221;) with p-values shown in Figure 4. CBPI success was pre-defined as a decrease in the PSS of one or more (out of a maximum possible score of 10) and a decrease in the PIS of two or more (out of a maximum possible score of 10).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 4: CBPI component endpoint p-values from the pivotal efficacy and field safety study of ranevetmab
<FONT STYLE="BACKGROUND-COLOR:#FFFFFF;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000004.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:439PX;HEIGHT:234PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Finally, veterinarian assessments were seen to be numerically superior to placebo for each composite variable at most evaluation points, and a statistically significant (p=0.0427) overall treatment effect (comparing treatment groups across all clinic visits) was seen for the assessment of &#8220;lameness at trot,&#8221; where a veterinarian visually assesses lameness while a dog trots.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ranevetmab was seen to be safe and well-tolerated in this study, with no significant adverse safety signals observed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ranevetmab Status
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have completed the production of a stable, high-expressing clonal cell line at a prior third-party contract manufacturer. Pilot batch scale-up has shown that&#160;ranevetmab is expressed at high concentrations from the clonal cell line, and is stable in liquid formulations. We have initiated the transfer of materials and processes for the production of ranevetmab to our biomanufacturing facility in Tullamore, Ireland.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	7
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage9"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU9">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	file
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	d
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	the effectiveness technical section
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	with
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	the CVM.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We expect BioNua to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	begin production of clinical supply of ranevetmab in the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	fourth quarter of 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	, to supply a pivotal safety study we anticipate will be initiated shortly thereafter.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area: Chronic Pain in Cats
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Frunevetmab&#160;(formerly &#8220;NV-02&#8221;) is a &#8220;100% cat&#8221; mAb targeting NGF, designed by PETization and being developed as a monthly subcutaneous injectable for chronic pain, specifically the pain associated with osteoarthritis in cats.&#160; All our clinical studies of frunevetmab assessing its potential as a therapeutic for chronic pain in cats have supported its safety and efficacy. Frunevetmab is a potential first-mover in chronic feline pain in the U.S., where there are currently no feline pain drugs approved for use for longer than three consecutive days. We have successfully completed proof-of-concept studies of frunevetmab. We have also successfully completed a pilot field safety and efficacy study, which enrolled 126 cats, as well as an earlier pilot safety study. We are seeking protocol concurrence from the CVM for a pivotal efficacy and field safety study of frunevetmab, which we intend to commence in the second half of 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The clinical trial drug substance has been manufactured by BioNua.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Market Opportunity and Current Treatment Limitations
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	According to the 2015-2016 American Pet Products Association National Pet Owners Survey and the European Pet Food Industry Federation&#8217;s Facts and Figures 2014, there are approximately 86&#160;million pet cats in&#160;the U.S. and approximately 72&#160;million pet cats in&#160;the EU and approximately 99 million pet cats in the wider European region.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Clinical studies indicate a significant majority of cats display radiographic evidence of degenerative joint disease, the progression of which is associated with increasing pain and disability. However, concerns about cats&#8217; sensitivity to NSAIDs has meant that in the U.S., no NSAID is approved for use in cats for more than three consecutive days.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	According to an April 2016 veterinary industry report on pain management by Brakke Consulting, only 20% of U.S. veterinarians surveyed were satisfied with pain management choices for cats (including both acute and chronic pain management options). Of the 80% of veterinarians who were dissatisfied, 43% said they needed drugs for long-term use in cats, 37% said they needed safer drugs, and 26% wanted products that were easier to administer. Oral dosing of cats is significantly harder than oral dosing of dogs and daily administration over a long time is especially challenging, making convenience of administration and reduced dosing frequency particularly compelling product attributes in the treatment of chronic feline conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The unmet medical need for safer pain therapeutics that can be administered to cats is supported by a proprietary report we commissioned from GfK in December 2013, which revealed that, of 390 veterinarians surveyed in the U.S., United Kingdom, France and Germany, between 86% and 98% would use a product such as&#160;frunevetmab for the treatment of chronic pain in cats.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Solution
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In proof-of-concept studies, frunevetmab was found to be safe and well tolerated following intravenous and subcutaneous administration in cats, and to have a pharmacokinetic profile indicating a prolonged circulation time after a single injection.&#160; These studies also provided early evidence of efficacy and lack of overt immunogenicity. A description of the PETization of frunevetmab and an early supportive proof-of-concept study that showed signs of efficacy two days following administration of frunevetmab to cats have been published in the peer-reviewed
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	American Journal of Veterinary Internal Medicine (JVIM)
</FONT>
	. A further supportive proof-of-concept study in 34 cats has also been published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	JVIM
</FONT>
	. We have also received positive data from a pilot safety study of frunevetmab in cats, which was conducted by an independent contract research organization (&#8220;CRO&#8221;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In May 2016 we successfully completed a pilot field study of frunevetmab which enrolled 126 cats at 15 clinical sites around the U.S. This placebo-controlled, randomized, double-blind study used monthly dosing: two administrations over a two month period. Cats were randomly assigned to frunevetmab or placebo on a 2:1 ratio.&nbsp;&nbsp;Treatment groups included both intravenous and subcutaneous administration. The key efficacy assessments were conducted using owner assessment metrology instruments, namely CSOM and the Feline Musculoskeletal Pain Index (&#8220;FMPI&#8221;). CSOM and FMPI owner assessments were measured at screening and on days 0, 14, 28, 42 and 56. Frunevetmab was found to be safe and effective by both routes of administration and, as there was no meaningful difference between the IV and SC treatment groups, they were combined for analysis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	8
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage10"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU10">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 5: CSOM summary data
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	from pilot field study of frunevetmab.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000005.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:378PX;HEIGHT:301PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	CSOM assesses change over time in three activities of the pet, selected by the owner, which evaluate the pet&#8217;s pain and disability. In this study, each activity received a score between 1 and 5, for a total score between 3 and 15. CSOM success was pre-defined as an overall improvement of at least 2 in the total CSOM score with no worsening of any individual activity&#8217;s score. On the rate of CSOM success, expressed as a percentage, frunevetmab-treated cats were numerically superior to the placebo group at day 28 onwards and significantly different at days 42 (p= 0.0479) and 56 (p=0.0033). A statistically significant improvement over placebo was seen in CSOM Global Assessment on both days where it was assessed: day 28 (p=0.0134) and day 56 (p=0.0030). The median CSOM scores of frunevetmab-treated cats were numerically superior to placebo at day 28 and significantly improved over placebo at day 42 (p=0.0077) and day 56 (p&lt;0.0001).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Figure 6: FMPI summary data from pilot field study of frunevetmab.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<IMG SRC="http://content.edgar-online.com/edgar_conv_img/2016/09/02/0001564590-16-024880_GUSQSWGNSWVO000006.JPG" TITLE="" ALT="" STYLE="WIDTH:382PX;HEIGHT:320PX;">
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	9
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage11"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU11">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	FMPI is an owner assessment tool
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	, in development at academic institutions,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	which uses 17
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	scor
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ed questions regarding a cat&#8217;s behavior, each scored between 1 and 5, for a possible score of between 17 and 85.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Using a reduction of 10 or more in the total FMPI score as a measure of success in an individual cat, the rates of success were expressed as a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	percentage in each treatment group.&nbsp;&nbsp;Frunevetmab-treated cats showed a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	statistically significant
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	improvement over placebo on this measure of FMPI success at days 42 (p=0.0076) and 56 (p=0.0242).&nbsp;&nbsp;Change in median FMPI score was also assessed:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	frunevetmab-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	treated cats were numerically superior to placebo at days 14 and 28 and showed a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	statistically significant improvement over placebo at days 42 (p=0.0002) and 56 (p=0.0160).
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Frunevetmab was seen to be safe and well-tolerated in this study, with no significant adverse safety signals observed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Frunevetmab Status
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	At our BioNua facility in Ireland we have established the production of&#160;frunevetmab in 200 liter bioreactors, which yield a quantity and quality sufficient for clinical supply. Our studies to date, including proof-of-concept studies (examining preliminary safety, immunogenicity, pharmacokinetics and safety and efficacy), a pilot safety study, and a pilot field study enrolling 126 cats (described above) have informed our preparation for two major studies of frunevetmab to commence in the fourth quarter of 2016: a pivotal efficacy and field safety study and a pivotal TAS study. We are seeking protocol concurrence from the CVM for the former study, and have received protocol concurrence for the TAS study.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area: Chronic Pain in Horses
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	NV-03 is a &#8220;100% horse&#8221; mAb targeting NGF, designed by PETization and being evaluated as a therapy for chronic joint pain in horses. We have generated supportive
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	in vivo
</FONT>
	proof-of-concept data for NV-03. Given our commercial focus on dogs and cats we are currently exploring a number of options regarding development of NV-03, including the potential for partnerships.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area: Immuno-Oncology (Cancer) in Dogs
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Immuno-oncology is an approach to fighting cancer that revolves around activating the immune system to attack tumors. In human medicine, blocking the interactions of PD-1 and a partner molecule, PD-L1, has resulted in approved &#8220;immune checkpoint inhibitor&#8221; therapies, such as Opdivo (nivolumab) and Keytruda (pembrolizumab), with attractive safety profiles and demonstrated efficacy against multiple tumor types.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our first mAbs in the area of immuno-oncology are &#8220;100% dog&#8221; mAbs targeting PD-1, designed by PETization and being developed as a treatment for cancer in dogs.&#160; Under our research and development collaboration with Zenoaq, we have initiated proof-of-concept studies of these mAbs. We have received confirmation from the USDA that anti-PD-1 mAbs will fall under its regulatory jurisdiction, and we have initiated discussions with the USDA regarding the requirements for conditional licensure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Market Opportunity and Current Treatment Limitations
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Dogs are susceptible to many of the same types of cancers that afflict humans. Epidemiological studies have indicated that cancer is the leading cause of death in dogs over 10 years of age, with 50 percent of older dogs developing cancer and approximately one in four dogs eventually dying because of cancer. Standards-of-care include surgery, radiotherapy, and chemotherapies repurposed from human treatments and often prescribed off-label. These interventions often carry significant limitations and potential impact on quality-of-life.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Checkpoint inhibitors have been particularly effective in patients whose tumors significantly express key checkpoint proteins (e.g. PD-L1). The academic literature documents a wide variety of canine tumor types which express PD-L1, including mast cell tumors (which represent 13% of dog cancers), B and T cell lymphomas (8% of dog cancers) and melanoma (5% of dog cancers). We believe that if we demonstrate the efficacy against multiple tumor types seen with approved human anti-PD-1 mAbs with an acceptable safety profile, it will represent a significant advance for canine cancer therapy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Solution
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our solution consists of&#160;&#8220;100% dog&#8221; mAbs targeting PD-1 designed by PETization, using a donor mAb identified by Zenoaq, and being developed as a treatment for cancer in dogs.&#160;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	10
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage12"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU12">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Status
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have completed
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	in vitro
</FONT>
	potency testing, demonstrating binding and inhibition of canine PD-1. We have produced sufficient material for further
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	in vitro
</FONT>
	characterization, and initiated a proof-of-concept pharmacokinetic, preliminary safety and immunogenicity study.&nbsp;&nbsp;We anticipate data from this work will be available by the end of 2016. We have received confirmation from the USDA that anti-PD-1 mAbs will fall under its regulatory jurisdiction, and we have initiated discussions with the USDA regarding the requirements for conditional licensure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area: Chronic Inflammation in Dogs and Cats
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have PETized canine and feline mAbs that have demonstrated potency in inhibiting TNF. TNF is a major inflammatory mediator and has a significant role in many systemic inflammatory conditions, including inflammatory bowel disease, various skin conditions and inflammatory joint diseases. Due to this pathophysiological importance, in human medicine anti-TNF
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	therapeutics as a class include some of the best-selling drugs in the world,
</FONT>
	including infliximab (Remicade), entanercept (Enbrel) and adalimumab (Humira). Cat and dog populations have a significant incidence of inflammatory conditions, in particular of the skin and gastrointestinal tract. We believe a safe, long-lasting and effective anti-TNF mAb would be an advantageous addition to veterinary therapeutics for chronic inflammatory conditions, currently managed by a wide variety of variably effective immuno-suppressives, small molecule anti-inflammatories, and other interventions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Market Opportunity and Current Treatment Limitations
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Chronic inflammation is seen in a variety of diseases in both dogs and cats, including inflammatory bowel disease, chronic kidney disease, joint inflammatory conditions, and a wide variety of skin conditions such as atopic dermatitis. These can significantly impact quality-of-life and have symptoms distressing for both pets and their owners.&#160;There is evidence to suggest the involvement of TNF in canine atopic dermatitis, inflammatory bowel disease in dogs, and chronic kidney disease in cats. Atopic dermatitis is estimated to affect 10% of dogs, and one study estimated 2.6% dogs present to clinics with gastroenteritis and 6.4% with diarrhea, indicating inflammatory bowel disease may be present in a significant population of pet dogs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Solution
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:3.33%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have PETized canine and feline mAbs that have demonstrated in vitro potency in inhibiting TNF.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Status
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	These research candidates will enter pharmacokinetic, preliminary safety and immunogenicity proof&#8209;of&#8209;concept studies in the second half of 2016
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Therapeutic Area: Allergy
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Allergy is a complex immune phenomenon responsible for a wide range of undesirable reactions to various stimuli. For example, a significant proportion of atopic dermatitis cases (which are responsible for approximately 10% of veterinarian visits) are related to allergies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Informed by supportive late-stage human data, we are researching several as-yet undisclosed biologic targets with potential efficacy in canine and feline allergic conditions
<FONT STYLE="COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Identification of New Product Candidates
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have an internal research and drug discovery team and we have established processes to identify and prioritize our target mAbs to be PETized. Preferred features of donor mAbs that we consider for PETization include:
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>

	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:3.33%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	a mAb to the target has demonstrated safety and efficacy in human clinical trials;

</P>
</TD>

	&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL';FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	the donor mAb retains its function, binding to the same target in the companion animal species;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
