</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2013 Long Term Incentive Plan
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September 2013, the Company&#8217;s board of directors approved a long-term incentive plan for its employees (including executive officers), directors and consultants pursuant to which in November 2013 the Company issued share options to purchase 215,799 ordinary shares and restricted share units to acquire 29,214 ordinary shares to employees, directors and consultants. The underlying ordinary shares had a fair value of $5.15 per share, but the awards had an exercise or conversion price, as applicable, of zero, as permitted under Australian law. Because Irish law requires the payment to an issuer of at least the nominal value of shares in order to acquire such shares from the issuer, any options or restricted share units with a zero exercise or conversion price became exercisable or convertible, as applicable, at their nominal value in August 2014 in anticipation of the Irish Exchange. This nominal value became $0.10 per ordinary share in September 2014 in connection with the Irish Exchange and was revised to $0.125 per ordinary share in connection with the four-for-five share consolidation in November 2014. In September 2014, the Company also issued share options to purchase 16,800 ordinary shares and restricted share units to acquire 21,240 ordinary shares to employees, directors and consultants. The underlying ordinary shares had a fair value of $6.35 per ordinary share, but the awards had an exercise or conversion price of the nominal value of $0.10 per ordinary share, which nominal value became $0.125 per ordinary share in connection with the four-for five share consolidation in November 2014. Except for share options and restricted share units held by directors (which vested in November 2014), share options and restricted share units held by employees and consultants vest in three equal tranches in November 2014,&#160;November 2015 and November 2016. The Company revised this plan in September 2014 and refers to this plan as its &#8220;2013 Plan.&#8221;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2014, the Company awarded employees 141,792 share options and restricted share units to acquire 16,427 ordinary shares.&nbsp;&nbsp;The underlying ordinary shares had a grant date fair value of $9.37.&nbsp;&nbsp;The share options and restricted share units have an exercise price and conversion price of $0.125 per ordinary share.&nbsp;&nbsp;The awards are subject to a specified performance condition and service period and they vest in tranches over one to three years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The 2013 Plan was terminated in connection with the Company&#8217;s initial public offering.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2013 Plan will continue to govern outstanding awards granted thereunder.&nbsp;&nbsp;Appropriate adjustments will be made in the number of authorized ordinary shares and other numerical limits in the 2013 Plan and in outstanding awards to prevent dilution or enlargement of participants&#8217; rights in the event of a share split or other change in the Company&#8217;s capital structure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Prior to its termination, the 2013 Plan was administered by the Company&#8217;s board of directors. Subject to the provisions of the 2013 Plan, the board of directors determined, in its discretion, the persons to whom, and the times at which, awards were granted, as well as the size, terms and conditions of each award, under the 2013 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;All awards are evidenced by a written agreement between the Company and the holder of the award.&nbsp;&nbsp;The board of directors has delegated to the Compensation Committee the authority to construe and interpret the terms of the 2013 Plan and awards granted under the 2013 Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the event of a change of control as described in the 2013 Plan, the acquiring or successor entity may assume or continue all or any awards outstanding under the 2013 Plan or substitute substantially equivalent awards.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any awards which are not assumed or continued in connection with a change of control or are not exercised or settled prior to the change of control will terminate effective as of the time of the change of control unless specified otherwise in an employment contract.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Compensation Committee may provide for the acceleration of vesting of any or all outstanding awards upon such terms and to such extent as it determines, except that the vesting of all awards held by members of the board of directors who are not employees will automatically be accelerated in full.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2013 Plan also authorizes the Compensation Committee, in its discretion and without the consent of any participant, to cancel each or any outstanding award denominated in ordinary shares upon a change of control in exchange for a payment to the participant with respect to each share subject to the cancelled award of an amount equal to the excess of the consideration to be paid per ordinary share in the change of control transaction over the exercise price per ordinary share, if any, under the award.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	F-22
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Equity Incentive
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Plan
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September 2014, the Company&#8217;s board of directors adopted, and in November 2014 the Company&#8217;s shareholders approved, the 2015 Equity Incentive Plan (&#8220;2015 Plan&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2015 Plan was amended by the board of directors in January 2015 and became effective on the date immediately prior to the date of the prospectus for initial public offering.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2015 Plan is intended to provide incentives that will assist the Company to attract, retain, and motivate employees, including officers, consultants and directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company may provide these incentives through the grant of share options, restricted share units, performance shares and units and other cash-based or share-based awards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A total of 1,280,000 of the Company&#8217;s ordinary shares were initially authorized and reserved for issuance under the 2015 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;This reserve has or will automatically increase on July 1 of each year through 2024 by an amount equal to the lesser of:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The ordinary shares available under the 2015 Plan will not be reduced by awards settled in cash, but will be reduced by ordinary shares withheld to satisfy tax withholding obligations with respect to ordinary share options (but not other types of awards).&nbsp;&nbsp;The gross number of ordinary shares issued upon the exercise of options exercised by means of a net exercise or by tender of previously-owned ordinary shares will be deducted from the ordinary shares available under the 2015 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Notwithstanding the foregoing, and subject to adjustment as described below, the maximum aggregate number of ordinary shares that may be subject to issuance at any given time under the 2015 Plan in connection with outstanding awards shall not exceed a number equal to ten percent of the Company&#8217;s total issued and outstanding ordinary shares (calculated on a non-diluted basis).&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Appropriate adjustments will be made in the number of authorized ordinary shares and other numerical limits in the 2015 Plan and in outstanding awards to prevent dilution or enlargement of participants&#8217; rights in the event of a share split or other change in the Company&#8217;s capital structure.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ordinary shares subject to awards which expire or are cancelled or forfeited will again become available for issuance under the 2015 Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In May 2015, 360,000 share options and 20,280 restricted share units to acquire ordinary shares were awarded to employees and directors under the 2015 Plan with a grant date fair value of $5.93 and $6.99, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The share option and restricted share units have an exercise price of $15.00 and a conversion price of $0.125 per ordinary share, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Except for 2,280 restricted share units held by directors (which vest immediately), the awards vest in tranches over one to five years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In June 2015, bonus share awards of an aggregate 42,691 ordinary shares were issued to employees subject to the payment of $0.125 per ordinary share.&nbsp;&nbsp;The underlying ordinary share had a grant date fair value of $7.115 per ordinary share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In August&#160;2015, the Company awarded two new employees share options to purchase 60,000&#160;ordinary shares and restricted share units to acquire 8,500&#160;ordinary shares with a grant date fair value of $2.71 and $4.97&#160;per share, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The share option and restricted share units have an exercise price of $5.10 and a conversion price of $0.125&#160;per ordinary share, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;The awards vest in tranches over one to four years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September&#160;2015, the Company awarded employees and directors restricted share units to acquire 298,834 ordinary shares, of which 296,059 were acquired, with grant date fair values of $4.26&#8209;$4.27.&nbsp;&nbsp;The restricted share units have a conversion price of $0.125&#160;per ordinary share.&nbsp;&nbsp;The restricted shares units granted to employees vest annually over four years commencing on July&#160;1, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The restricted share units granted to directors vest on July&#160;1, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November&#160;2015, the Company awarded a new employee restricted share units to acquire 2,000&#160;ordinary shares with a grant date fair value of $4.76
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	.
</FONT>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;The restricted share units have a conversion price of $0.125&#160;per ordinary share.&nbsp;&nbsp;The restricted share units granted vest on September&#160;21, 2016.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The aggregate intrinsic value of share-based awards as of June&#160;30, 2016 was $2.1&#160;million, of which $0.1 million related to vested share-based awards and $2.0&#160;million related to unvested share-based awards

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU86">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2013, the Company entered into an agreement with a financial advisor for the provision of certain financial services. Pursuant to the agreement, the financial advisor elected to receive payment of fees in ordinary shares. In November 2013, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Company issued 8,849 SIRPS Preference Shares at $5.18 per share to the financial advisor.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 15. Valuation of Share Awards
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Prior to February 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The fair value of each share option is estimated on the date of grant using the binomial option-pricing model.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company was a private company until February&#160;2015 and lacked company-specific historical and implied volatility information.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore, it has estimated its expected share volatility based on the historical volatility of its publicly traded peer companies until such time as it has adequate historical data regarding the volatility of its own traded share price.&nbsp;&nbsp;The expected term of the Company&#8217;s share options has been determined utilizing the &#8220;simplified&#8221; method as the Company has insufficient historical experience for share options overall, rendering existing historical experience irrelevant to expectations for current grants.&nbsp;&nbsp;The risk-free interest rate is determined by reference to the appropriate reserve bank yield in effect at the time of grant of the award for time periods approximately equal to the expected term of the award. Expected dividend yield is based on the fact that the Company has never paid cash dividends and does not expect to pay any cash dividends in the foreseeable future.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair value of the underlying ordinary shares considered the price per share paid by investors in the Company&#8217;s private financings, including the Series B Preference Shares in May 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Post February 2015
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Since completion of the Company&#8217;s initial public offering, the fair value of the underlying ordinary shares has been based on the price per share quoted on the NASDAQ Global Market at the date of grant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The fair value of the share awards was estimated using the following assumptions:

	&#160;
</FONT>

<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU87">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The total intrinsic value of share options exercised was $0.5&#160;million, $0.5&#160;million and $nil in 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In addition to the share options described above, the Company has granted restricted share units to its directors, employees and consultants. Restricted share units are valued at the fair value of the underlying ordinary shares as of the date of grant. The fair value of the ordinary shares issuable upon conversion of restricted share units considered the price per share paid by investors in the Company&#8217;s private financings, including the SIRPS Preference Shares in July 2013. The ordinary shares subject to the restricted share units are generally issued when they vest. The table below presents the Company&#8217;s restricted share unit activity for fiscal years 2016 and 2015:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The total intrinsic value of restricted share units converted was $0.1&#160;million, $0.2&#160;million and $nil in 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Share-Based Compensation
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Company recognizes share-based compensation expense for only the portion of awards that are expected to vest. In developing a forfeiture rate estimate, the Company has considered its historical experience to estimate pre-vesting forfeitures for service-based awards. The impact of a forfeiture rate adjustment will be recognized in full in the period of adjustment, and if the actual forfeiture rate is materially different from the Company&#8217;s estimate, the Company may be required to record adjustments to share-based compensation expense in future periods.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Company recorded share-based compensation expense related to share options and restricted share units for the fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014 as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;

<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU88">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	. Commitments and Contingencies
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Indemnities and Guarantees
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Company has made certain indemnities and guarantees, under which it may be required to make payments to a guaranteed or indemnified party, in relation to certain transactions. The Company indemnifies its directors and officers to the extent permitted under the Company&#8217;s Constitution and the Irish Companies Act and provides expense advancement for our directors and executive officers for certain expenses, including attorneys&#8217; fees, judgments, fines, and settlements amounts incurred by a director or executive officer in any action or proceeding arising out of their services as one of our directors or executive officer.&nbsp;&nbsp;The duration of these indemnities and guarantees varies and, in certain cases, is indefinite. These indemnities and guarantees do not provide for any limitation of the maximum potential future payments the Company could be obligated to make. Historically, the Company has not been obligated to make any payments for these obligations and no liabilities have been recorded for these indemnities and guarantees in the accompanying balance sheets.
</P>

	The Company occupies research facilities in Australia and expects to enter a lease arrangement in the near future, if this agreement was in place at balance date the operating leases amount would increase by a total $0.2 million (&lt; 1 year $0.1 million, 1-3 year $0.1 million)

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Operating Leases
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Company entered into a lease for its office in Melbourne, Australia commencing December 2013 for a period of five years.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of June&#160;30, 2016 and June&#160;30, 2015 commitments totaled $0.2&#160;million and $0.4&#160;million, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Rent expense was $0.2&#160;million $0.2 million and $0.1&#160;million for fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Included in rent expense is a build-out incentive of $26,000, $26,000 and $11,000 for the fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;A portion of the incentive paid by the landlord is to be repaid by the Company if the lease is terminated early, determined by the unexpired term of the lease over the original 60&#8209;month lease term.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The Company entered into a lease for a facility in Tullamore, Ireland commencing September&#160;2015 for a period of 10&#160;years, with an option to purchase the building.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of June 30, 2016, commitments on this lease totaled $1.1&#160;million.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Purchase Obligations
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In connection with the development of biologics, the Company had open contracts with suppliers for goods and services of $0.5 million and $0.7&#160;million as of June&#160;30, 2016 and June&#160;30, 2015, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Other
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	BioNua is eligible under an agreement with the IDA to receive cash as grant income.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company may not, without the prior written consent of the IDA, assign, dispose, mortgage or change any assets which have been funded by the IDA.&nbsp;&nbsp;The IDA may revoke or reduce the grant if there is a serious breach of the agreement or if the Company enters a form of administration, transfers any intellectual property developed under the grant outside Ireland or disposes of BioNua.&nbsp;&nbsp;The IDA may require the Company to repay grant income paid previously to the Company if the Company commits a serious breach of the agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>

<A NAME="NVET-10K_20160630_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU89">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	. Income Taxes
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	There is no provision for income taxes because the Company has historically incurred operating losses and maintains a full valuation allowance against its net deferred tax assets. The reported amount of income tax expense differs from the amount that would result from applying domestic federal statutory tax rates to pretax losses primarily because of changes in valuation allowance. In all periods presented, all revenue was earned in Australia.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A reconciliation of the statutory income tax rate to the Company&#8217;s effective income tax rate is as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	As of June&#160;30, 2016 and 2015, the Company had total deferred tax assets of $6.0&#160;million and $2.2&#160;million, respectively. Management has evaluated the factors bearing upon the reliability of its deferred tax assets, which consist principally of tax loss carry forwards in United Sates, Australia and Ireland. &#160;&#160;Our management concluded that it is more likely than not that all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized in the future due our lack of taxable income prospects for the foreseeable future.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore, the deferred tax assets are reduced by a full valuation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Utilization of tax loss carry forwards is subject to potential limitation as a consequence of the Australian loss recoupment rules and future ownership changes, future capital raisings or ongoing changes in the Company&#8217;s business. Given the change of ownership that occurred in September 2014 (see Note&#160;1), the Australian tax authorities could argue that there has been a change in the Company&#8217;s underlying business in Australia, which may result in these tax losses never being recoverable. Should this occur, future Australian taxable profits would be taxed at the full corporate rate of 30%.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending on the actual amount of any limitation on the Company&#8217;s ability to use its tax loss carry forwards, a significant portion of its future taxable income could be taxable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Changes in the valuation allowance for deferred tax assets during fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014 were as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Note 18. Related Party Transaction
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;;FONT-SIZE:6PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ridge Biotechnology Consulting, LLC is owned and operated by Dr.&#160;Robert Gearing, the brother of David Gearing, a co-founder of the Company and its Chief Scientific Officer. In October 2010, the Company entered into a consulting agreement with Ridge Biotechnology Consulting, LLC for the provision of services to the Company. The agreement was superseded by agreements entered into in April 2011 and April 2012, and a new consulting agreement with Ridge Biotechnology Consulting, LLC was entered into in January 2014. The Company recorded general and administrative expense of $39,000, $0.2&#160;million and $0.1&#160;million in fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively, related to these agreements. As of June&#160;30, 2016 and 2015, there was $13,000 and $19,000 payable to Ridge Biotechnology Consulting, LLC, respectively. Dr.&#160;Robert Gearing was also a party to a 2012 agreement with the Company pursuant to which the Company issued Dr.&#160;Gearing 4,424 ordinary shares in fiscal year&#160;2014 and 6,250 ordinary shares in fiscal year&#160;2013, with an aggregate value of $48,000, for arranging certain research and development services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:2.63%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Dr.&#160;Andrew Gearing is a former director, a co-founder of the Company and a brother of David Gearing, a co-founder of the Company and its Chief Scientific Officer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Dr.&#160;Andrew Gearing serves on the board of directors of Biocomm Square Pty Ltd. In August 2010 and August 2013, the Company entered into consulting agreements with Biocomm Square Pty Ltd for research and development support services.&nbsp;&nbsp;These agreements were superseded by a new consulting agreement in December 2013, which was amended in April 2014, September 2015 and June 2016. In addition, the Company entered into an agreement with Biocomm Square Pty Ltd in November 2011 for assistance in obtaining partnering arrangements with Japanese entities. This agreement was terminated in September 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recorded research and development expense of $0.2&#160;million, $0.2&#160;million and $0.2&#160;million in fiscal years 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively, related to these agreements. As of June&#160;30, 2016 and 2015, there was $12,000 and $17,000 payable to Biocomm Square Pty Ltd, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	Disclosed in this report any change in the registrant&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting that occurred during the registrant&#8217;s most recent fiscal quarter (the registrant&#8217;s fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the registrant&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting; and

	In connection with the annual report on Form 10-K of Nexvet Biopharma public limited company (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) for the period ended June&#160;30, 2016 as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on the date hereof (the &#8220;Report&#8221;), I certify, pursuant to 18 U.S.C. &#167; 1350, as adopted pursuant to &#167; 906 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, that:
